The ATE treatment elicits FCs by a factor of at most four but lower than two for the vast majority of genes, while for ISO we observed a few genes with higher magnitudes. These differences are even more pronounced in terms of significance, with all but one gene with a pFC > 10−10 for ATE, while a sizable number of them had much smaller p-values for ISO (Additional file 1: Figure S9a-b). As a consequence we found that a signed significance value, that we termed Differential Expression Index (DEI), was the most useful single measure to characterize DE across a range of significance values. The DEI is defined as the product of the sign of the log FC and the log of its p-value:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
